  [✓] llm.query Messages=[{"Role":"system","Content":"# Step Compiler\n\nYou are the PLang compiler. The planner gave you the **set of actions** a step uses (unordered). You order them, nest modifiers, fill parameter values from the step text, and emit one \u0060formal\u0060 line plus the matching \u0060actions[]\u0060.\n\nEach picked action\u0027s parameter schema, **Notes**, **Examples**, and the **Type reference** are in the user message below \u2014 authoritative for that action\u0027s shape. Read them first. This prompt is the cross-cutting kernel.\n\n## Core rule: map the clauses \u2014 nothing more, nothing less\n\nWalk the step text clause by clause. Each clause that does work maps to exactly the action(s) it names.\n\n- **Emit only what a clause names.** If the text gives no value for an optional parameter, omit it. If no clause calls for a second action, don\u0027t add one \u2014 never invent a peer or modifier (no stray \u0060variable.get\u0060, \u0060file.read\u0060, \u0060cache.wrap\u0060) the text didn\u0027t ask for.\n- **Never return an empty \u0060actions\u0060 list for a step that has a clause.** Every real step maps to at least one action: \u0060set %x% = %y%\u0060 \u2192 one \u0060variable.set\u0060; \u0060call X\u0060 \u2192 one \u0060goal.call\u0060. If the planner\u0027s set genuinely lacks a needed action, emit the \u0060missing-actions\u0060 error \u2014 never return nothing.\n\nMost steps are one action per clause. \u0022This looks too simple\u0022 is almost always right.\n\n## Write \u0060formal\u0060 first\n\nA one-line render of the chain; \u0060actions[]\u0060 then mirrors it exactly.\n\n\u0060module.action(ParamName=value, ...)\u0060 \u2014 real schema param names. Quote strings; keep \u0060%vars%\u0060 verbatim; numbers/bools unquoted; lists \u0060[...]\u0060; objects \u0060{k:v}\u0060.\n- Modifier follows its host with \u0060 | \u0060 : \u0060host(...) | error.handle(Actions=[recovery(...)])\u0060\n- Peer follows with \u0060 , \u0060 : \u0060condition.if(...) , goal.call(...)\u0060\n- Nested action values use \u0060[...]\u0060 with the same syntax.\n\n\u0060formal\u0060 and \u0060actions[]\u0060 MUST match exactly \u2014 every \u0060Param=value\u0060 in one appears in the other, no extras either way.\n\n## Modifiers vs peers\n\nOnly THREE actions are modifiers \u2014 \u0060error.handle\u0060, \u0060cache.wrap\u0060, \u0060timeout.after\u0060 \u2014 and they go in the host action\u0027s \u0060modifiers[]\u0060. Use one only when the step has a clause like \u0060on error \u2026\u0060, \u0060cache for \u2026\u0060, \u0060timeout after \u2026\u0060. A \u0060cache=\u0060 *parameter* on \u0060llm.query\u0060 is NOT cache.wrap.\n\nEverything else (\u0060goal.call\u0060, \u0060variable.set\u0060, \u0060condition.if\u0060, \u0060loop.foreach\u0060, \u0060output.write\u0060, \u0060file.*\u0060, \u0060error.throw\u0060, \u2026) is a **peer** in the top-level \u0060actions[]\u0060, never in \u0060modifiers[]\u0060. \u0060if X, call Y\u0060 and \u0060foreach X, call Y\u0060 are two peers.\n\n## \u0060write to %x%\u0060 and \u0060%!data%\u0060\n\n\u0060\u2026, write to %x%\u0060 \u2192 a trailing peer \u0060variable.set(Name=%x%, Value=%!data%)\u0060 after the producer (never a modifier). \u0060%!data%\u0060 is the immediately preceding action\u0027s return value \u2014 use it ONLY to thread one action\u0027s result into the next when the text says so. It is not a fill-in for an unsupplied slot.\n\n## Output shape\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060json\n{\u0022formal\u0022:\u0022...\u0022,\u0022actions\u0022:[...],\u0022confidence\u0022:\u0022VeryHigh|High|Medium|Low|VeryLow\u0022,\u0022explanation\u0022:\u0022...\u0022,\u0022errors\u0022:[],\u0022warnings\u0022:[]}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nEach action: \u0060{module, action, parameters:[{name, value, type}], modifiers?:[...]}\u0060. \u0060module\u0060 is a single identifier: \u0060ui.render\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022module\u0022:\u0022ui\u0022,\u0022action\u0022:\u0022render\u0022}\u0060, never \u0060{\u0022module\u0022:\u0022ui.render\u0022,...}\u0060. Omit \u0060explanation\u0060 at High/VeryHigh; otherwise one sentence on the uncertainty. Drop confidence to Low/VeryLow when the verb doesn\u0027t really match any action you were given.\n\n## Parameters \u0026 types\n\n- \u0060name\u0060 is always the literal schema property name (\u0060Name\u0060, \u0060Value\u0060, \u0060GoalName\u0060, \u2026). A \u0060%var%\u0060 marker in a schema means \u0022takes a variable reference\u0022 \u2014 it is never a parameter name and says nothing about the runtime type. Don\u0027t raise warnings over type or letter-case differences.\n- Type names come from the per-step Type reference (primitive names \u002B kind table \u002B catalog types) \u2014 don\u0027t invent. \u0060text\u0060 not \u0060string\u0060; \u0060number\u0060 carries \u0060int/long/decimal/double\u0060 as its *kind*; lists are \u0060list\u003CT\u003E\u0060. A JSON object/array value uses \u0060type:\u0022json\u0022\u0060 as a structured value.\n- Omit nullable params (\u0060?\u0060) when the text gives no value. NEVER emit \u0060\u0022\u0022\u0060 or copy a type descriptor (\u0060actor?\u0060, \u0060eventtype\u0060) into a value slot.\n\n## Intermediates \u0026 compound conditions\n\n- To branch on a producer\u0027s property, capture into a temp \u0060__conditionReturn__\u0060 and reference \u0060%__conditionReturn__.X%\u0060.\n- \u0060if A and B, call C\u0060 \u2192 two \u0060condition.if\u0060 peers \u002B the \u0060goal.call\u0060; add \u0060warnings:[{\u0022key\u0022:\u0022expanded-condition\u0022,\u0022message\u0022:\u0022...\u0022}]\u0060.\n\n## Errors\n\n- \u0060missing-actions\u0060 (top-level, exact key) \u2014 the set lacks an action the step needs; emit and stop, don\u0027t fabricate a partial chain.\n- Also: \u0060actionNotFound\u0060, \u0060insufficientContext\u0060 (top-level); \u0060ambiguousMapping\u0060, \u0060possibleTypo\u0060 (per action).\n\nNever invent action names (\u0060list.append\u0060/\u0060push\u0060/\u0060insert\u0060 don\u0027t exist \u2014 use \u0060list.add\u0060). Preserve \u0060%name%\u0060 literally everywhere, including \u0060return\u0060.\n"},{"Role":"user","Content":"## Step text (the line to compile)\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\nllm.query Messages=[{"Role":"system","Content":"# Step Compiler\n\nYou are the PLang compiler. The planner gave you the **set of actions** a step uses (unordered). You order them, nest modifiers, fill parameter values from the step text, and emit one \u0060formal\u0060 line plus the matching \u0060actions[]\u0060.\n\nEach picked action\u0027s parameter schema, **Notes**, **Examples**, and the **Type reference** are in the user message below \u2014 authoritative for that action\u0027s shape. Read them first. This prompt is the cross-cutting kernel.\n\n## Core rule: map the clauses \u2014 nothing more, nothing less\n\nWalk the step text clause by clause. Each clause that does work maps to exactly the action(s) it names.\n\n- **Emit only what a clause names.** If the text gives no value for an optional parameter, omit it. If no clause calls for a second action, don\u0027t add one \u2014 never invent a peer or modifier (no stray \u0060variable.get\u0060, \u0060file.read\u0060, \u0060cache.wrap\u0060) the text didn\u0027t ask for.\n- **Never return an empty \u0060actions\u0060 list for a step that has a clause.** Every real step maps to at least one action: \u0060set %x% = %y%\u0060 \u2192 one \u0060variable.set\u0060; \u0060call X\u0060 \u2192 one \u0060goal.call\u0060. If the planner\u0027s set genuinely lacks a needed action, emit the \u0060missing-actions\u0060 error \u2014 never return nothing.\n\nMost steps are one action per clause. \u0022This looks too simple\u0022 is almost always right.\n\n## Write \u0060formal\u0060 first\n\nA one-line render of the chain; \u0060actions[]\u0060 then mirrors it exactly.\n\n\u0060module.action(ParamName=value, ...)\u0060 \u2014 real schema param names. Quote strings; keep \u0060%vars%\u0060 verbatim; numbers/bools unquoted; lists \u0060[...]\u0060; objects \u0060{k:v}\u0060.\n- Modifier follows its host with \u0060 | \u0060 : \u0060host(...) | error.handle(Actions=[recovery(...)])\u0060\n- Peer follows with \u0060 , \u0060 : \u0060condition.if(...) , goal.call(...)\u0060\n- Nested action values use \u0060[...]\u0060 with the same syntax.\n\n\u0060formal\u0060 and \u0060actions[]\u0060 MUST match exactly \u2014 every \u0060Param=value\u0060 in one appears in the other, no extras either way.\n\n## Modifiers vs peers\n\nOnly THREE actions are modifiers \u2014 \u0060error.handle\u0060, \u0060cache.wrap\u0060, \u0060timeout.after\u0060 \u2014 and they go in the host action\u0027s \u0060modifiers[]\u0060. Use one only when the step has a clause like \u0060on error \u2026\u0060, \u0060cache for \u2026\u0060, \u0060timeout after \u2026\u0060. A \u0060cache=\u0060 *parameter* on \u0060llm.query\u0060 is NOT cache.wrap.\n\nEverything else (\u0060goal.call\u0060, \u0060variable.set\u0060, \u0060condition.if\u0060, \u0060loop.foreach\u0060, \u0060output.write\u0060, \u0060file.*\u0060, \u0060error.throw\u0060, \u2026) is a **peer** in the top-level \u0060actions[]\u0060, never in \u0060modifiers[]\u0060. \u0060if X, call Y\u0060 and \u0060foreach X, call Y\u0060 are two peers.\n\n## \u0060write to %x%\u0060 and \u0060%!data%\u0060\n\n\u0060\u2026, write to %x%\u0060 \u2192 a trailing peer \u0060variable.set(Name=%x%, Value=%!data%)\u0060 after the producer (never a modifier). \u0060%!data%\u0060 is the immediately preceding action\u0027s return value \u2014 use it ONLY to thread one action\u0027s result into the next when the text says so. It is not a fill-in for an unsupplied slot.\n\n## Output shape\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060json\n{\u0022formal\u0022:\u0022...\u0022,\u0022actions\u0022:[...],\u0022confidence\u0022:\u0022VeryHigh|High|Medium|Low|VeryLow\u0022,\u0022explanation\u0022:\u0022...\u0022,\u0022errors\u0022:[],\u0022warnings\u0022:[]}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nEach action: \u0060{module, action, parameters:[{name, value, type}], modifiers?:[...]}\u0060. \u0060module\u0060 is a single identifier: \u0060ui.render\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022module\u0022:\u0022ui\u0022,\u0022action\u0022:\u0022render\u0022}\u0060, never \u0060{\u0022module\u0022:\u0022ui.render\u0022,...}\u0060. Omit \u0060explanation\u0060 at High/VeryHigh; otherwise one sentence on the uncertainty. Drop confidence to Low/VeryLow when the verb doesn\u0027t really match any action you were given.\n\n## Parameters \u0026 types\n\n- \u0060name\u0060 is always the literal schema property name (\u0060Name\u0060, \u0060Value\u0060, \u0060GoalName\u0060, \u2026). A \u0060%var%\u0060 marker in a schema means \u0022takes a variable reference\u0022 \u2014 it is never a parameter name and says nothing about the runtime type. Don\u0027t raise warnings over type or letter-case differences.\n- Type names come from the per-step Type reference (primitive names \u002B kind table \u002B catalog types) \u2014 don\u0027t invent. \u0060text\u0060 not \u0060string\u0060; \u0060number\u0060 carries \u0060int/long/decimal/double\u0060 as its *kind*; lists are \u0060list\u003CT\u003E\u0060. A JSON object/array value uses \u0060type:\u0022json\u0022\u0060 as a structured value.\n- Omit nullable params (\u0060?\u0060) when the text gives no value. NEVER emit \u0060\u0022\u0022\u0060 or copy a type descriptor (\u0060actor?\u0060, \u0060eventtype\u0060) into a value slot.\n\n## Intermediates \u0026 compound conditions\n\n- To branch on a producer\u0027s property, capture into a temp \u0060__conditionReturn__\u0060 and reference \u0060%__conditionReturn__.X%\u0060.\n- \u0060if A and B, call C\u0060 \u2192 two \u0060condition.if\u0060 peers \u002B the \u0060goal.call\u0060; add \u0060warnings:[{\u0022key\u0022:\u0022expanded-condition\u0022,\u0022message\u0022:\u0022...\u0022}]\u0060.\n\n## Errors\n\n- \u0060missing-actions\u0060 (top-level, exact key) \u2014 the set lacks an action the step needs; emit and stop, don\u0027t fabricate a partial chain.\n- Also: \u0060actionNotFound\u0060, \u0060insufficientContext\u0060 (top-level); \u0060ambiguousMapping\u0060, \u0060possibleTypo\u0060 (per action).\n\nNever invent action names (\u0060list.append\u0060/\u0060push\u0060/\u0060insert\u0060 don\u0027t exist \u2014 use \u0060list.add\u0060). Preserve \u0060%name%\u0060 literally everywhere, including \u0060return\u0060.\n"},{"Role":"user","Content":"## Step text (the line to compile)\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\nllm.query Messages=%messages%, Schema={description: string, steps: list\u003C{index: int, actions: list\u003Cstring\u003E, confidence: string, explanation?: string}\u003E}, cache=%!build.cache%, write to %plan%\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n## What to map to \u2014 the planner picked these actions\n\nllm.query, variable.set\n\n## Action detail (parameters \u002B notes)\n\n\n\n\n## llm.query\n\nDescription:\nSend prompts to an LLM and receive structured or streamed responses, with optional tool use\n\nSend a conversation (system \u002B user messages) to an LLM and return the response, with optional schema or tool use\n\nParameters:\n  - Messages: list\u003Cllmmessage\u003E\n  - Tools: list\u003Cgoal.call\u003E?\n  - OnToolCall: goal.call?\n  - OnValidateResponse: goal.call?\n  - OnStream: goal.call?\n  - Schema: object?\n  - Format: text?\n  - Model: text?\n  - ContinuePreviousConversation: bool = false\n  - Temperature: number = 0\n  - TopP: number?\n  - MaxTokens: number = 16000\n  - MaxToolCalls: number = 10\n  - MaxValidationRetries: number = 0\n  - Cache: bool = true\n\u2192 returns data\n\nNotes:\n\u0060llm.query system=\u2026, user=\u2026\u0060 \u2192 single \u0060Messages\u0060 parameter of type \u0060list\u003Cllmmessage\u003E\u0060:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060json\n[{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022system\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022\u2026\u0022},{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022user\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022\u2026\u0022}]\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n\u0060schema=\u2026\u0060 \u2192 \u0060Schema\u0060 parameter. If JSON-shaped, set \u0060\u0022type\u0022: \u0022json\u0022\u0060 and emit as a structured object (not a string containing JSON).\n\nExamples:\n  Step text: \u0060system: analyze sentiment, user: %comment%, schema: {sentiment: string}, write to %result%\u0060\nMapping: \u0060llm.query Messages([list\u003CLlmMessage\u003E] [{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022system\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022analyze sentiment\u0022},{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022user\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022%comment%\u0022}]), Schema([string] {sentiment: string}) | variable.set Name([string] %result%), Value([object] %!data%)\u0060\n\n\n\n## variable.set [no-cache]\n\nDescription:\nRead, write, and inspect PLang runtime variables in the current scope\n\nAssign a value to a named variable, optionally coercing to a type or setting only when unset\n\nParameters:\n  - Name: %var%\n  - Value: object\n  - Type: type?\n  - AsDefault: bool = false\n\u2192 returns data\n\nNotes:\n\u0060set %x% = \u2026\u0060 is ONE \u0060variable.set\u0060. Emit the \u0060Type\u0060 parameter only when the step gives an explicit \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E[/\u003Ckind\u003E] [strict]\u0060 or \u0060(\u003Ckind\u003E)\u0060 annotation (see the Type reference block); otherwise omit and let the runtime infer.\n\n\u0060set %x% = \u2026 as default\u0060 / \u0022default to\u0022 / \u0022only if unset\u0022 \u2192 plain \u0060variable.set\u0060 with \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022AsDefault\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:true,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022bool\u0022}\u0060. NEVER \u0060code.setDefault\u0060 (that picks a signing/crypto provider \u2014 unrelated to assigning a \u0060%variable%\u0060).\n\n\u0060\u003Cproducer\u003E, write to %x%\u0060 \u2192 the producer \u002B a trailing PEER \u0060variable.set(Name=%x%, Value=%!data%)\u0060 (never a modifier). Don\u0027t add a separate \u0060Type\u0060 \u2014 the producer\u0027s \u0060Data\u003CT\u003E\u0060 (its \u0060\u2192 returns\u0060 line) carries it.\n\nExamples:\n  Step text: \u0060set %x% = 5\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %x%), Value([number] 5)\u0060 \u2014 no \u0060Type\u0060; runtime stamps \u0060{name:\u0022number\u0022,kind:\u0022int\u0022}\u0060 from the literal.\n\n  Step text: \u0060set default %enabled% = true\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %enabled%), Value([bool] true), AsDefault([bool] true)\u0060 \u2014 no \u0060Type\u0060; the value is plain.\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %doc% = \u0022readme.md\u0022 as text\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %doc%), Value([text] readme.md), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022})\u0060\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %img% = \u0022real.gif\u0022 as image/gif strict\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %img%), Value([text] real.gif), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022image\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022gif\u0022,\u0022strict\u0022:true})\u0060\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %n% = \u002242\u0022 as int\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %n%), Value([text] 42), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022int\u0022})\u0060 \u2014 \u0060int\u0060 is a kind of \u0060number\u0060, never a top-level name.\n\n\n\n\n\n## Variables in scope (from prior steps)\n\n\n\n## Type reference\n\n**Primitive type names** (use these as the top-level \u0060name\u0060 in a parameter \u0060type\u0060 field): text, number, bool, object, list, dict, datetime, date, time, duration, guid, image, video, audio, path, bytes\n\n**Every parameter wrapper has three fields**: \u0060name\u0060 (the parameter name), \u0060value\u0060 (the actual value), \u0060type\u0060 (the value\u0027s PLang type as a structured \u0060{name, kind?, strict?}\u0060 dict). \u0060type\u0060 is ONE field \u2014 never split into sibling \u0060type\u0060 \u002B \u0060kind\u0060 keys.\n\nExamples of complete wrappers:\n\n- raw value \u00605\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:5,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022int\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u00603.14\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:3.14,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022decimal\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060\u0022hi\u0022\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:\u0022hi\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060\u0022readme.md\u0022\u0060 (a string literal \u2014 its value IS the 9 characters \u0022readme.md\u0022, which is text, NOT a markdown document) \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:\u0022readme.md\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060true\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:true,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022bool\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060{a:1, b:2}\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:{\u0022a\u0022:1,\u0022b\u0022:2},\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022object\u0022}}\u0060\n\nA bare string literal is \u0060text\u0060 with **no kind** \u2014 never promote it by its spelling. A file extension in a literal (\u0060.md\u0060, \u0060.jpg\u0060, \u0060.csv\u0060) does NOT make the value that kind: the value is the path string, not the content it points at. A \u0060kind\u0060 on a literal comes from exactly two places, never the spelling:\n- an explicit \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E\u0060 the developer wrote, or\n- a producing action that read the real content/path (e.g. \u0060read file.md\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{text, md}\u0060 \u2014 there the value IS the markdown).\n\nA reference fundamental (\u0060image\u0060, \u0060video\u0060, \u0060audio\u0060, \u0060path\u0060) is never tagged onto a raw literal \u2014 there is no image literal, only a path. The LLM emits \u0060{name: image}\u0060 only when the developer wrote \u0060as image\u0060; the runtime parses the kind from the path.\n\nA parameter whose DECLARED schema type is \u0060type\u0060 (e.g. \u0060variable.set.Type\u0060) carries a type entity AS ITS VALUE. The wrapper is:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022Type\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022md\u0022},\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022type\u0022}}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n\u0060value\u0060 is the type entity \u0060{name, kind?, strict?}\u0060; \u0060type\u0060 is the wrapper\u0027s own type field, set to \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022type\u0022}\u0060.\n\n**Kind vocabulary** \u2014 for each \u0060name\u0060, the kinds you may emit under it (a kind is the file extension or numeric precision):\n\n| name | kind |\n|---|---|\n| audio | m4a, ogg, mp3, wav, flac, aac |\n| text | xml, csv, yaml, md, txt, ini, json, yml |\n| video | flv, webm, avi, mp4, mov, mkv |\n| image | tiff, png, heic, svg, gif, bmp, tif, jpeg, jpg, webp |\n| number | int, long, decimal, double |\n\n\nRules:\n- \u0060string\u0060 is NOT a name \u2014 use \u0060text\u0060. \u0060int\u0060/\u0060long\u0060/\u0060decimal\u0060/\u0060double\u0060 are NOT names \u2014 use \u0060number\u0060 with the precision as the kind.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cname\u003E\u0022}\u0060. For a reference fundamental (\u0060image\u0060/\u0060video\u0060/\u0060audio\u0060/\u0060path\u0060) the runtime parses the kind from the value\u0027s path; for \u0060text\u0060 no kind is derived from a literal\u0027s spelling.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cname\u003E\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022\u003Ckind\u003E\u0022}\u0060.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E strict\u0060 \u2192 adds \u0060\u0022strict\u0022:true\u0060. Strict on a name with no kind is allowed (no-op).\n- Step-text \u0060(\u003Ckind\u003E)\u0060 after a write target \u2192 match the kind to its name in the table above. \u0060(json)\u0060/\u0060(csv)\u0060/\u0060(xml)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060text\u0060; \u0060(int)\u0060/\u0060(long)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060number\u0060; \u0060(gif)\u0060/\u0060(jpg)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060image\u0060. Unknown free strings pass through as \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cthat\u003E\u0022}\u0060.\n\n\n**Catalog types referenced by this step\u0027s actions** (record/enum field shapes; primitives stay in the Primitive list above, kinds in the table above):\n\n- \u0060goal\u0060: { name: text, description: text, comment: text, visibility: visibility, inputParameters: dict\u003Ctext,text\u003E }\n- \u0060llmmessage\u0060: { role: text, content: text, images: list\u003Ctext\u003E }\n- \u0060visibility\u0060: Private | Public\n\n\n## Compile this exact line\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\nllm.query Messages=%messages%, Schema={description: string, steps: list\u003C{index: int, actions: list\u003Cstring\u003E, confidence: string, explanation?: string}\u003E}, cache=%!build.cache%, write to %plan%\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nProduce the actions for this step \u2014 map the line above verbatim. Copy every identifier, path, and argument exactly as written (e.g. a goal name \u0060Folder/Goal\u0060 keeps \u0060/Goal\u0060; a \u0060%var%\u0060 stays a \u0060%var%\u0060).\n"}], Schema={description: string, steps: list\u003C{index: int, actions: list\u003Cstring\u003E, confidence: string, explanation?: string}\u003E}, cache=%!build.cache%, write to System.Collections.Generic.Dictionary`2[System.String,System.Object]\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n## What to map to \u2014 the planner picked these actions\n\nllm.query, variable.set\n\n## Action detail (parameters \u002B notes)\n\n\n\n\n## llm.query\n\nDescription:\nSend prompts to an LLM and receive structured or streamed responses, with optional tool use\n\nSend a conversation (system \u002B user messages) to an LLM and return the response, with optional schema or tool use\n\nParameters:\n  - Messages: list\u003Cllmmessage\u003E\n  - Tools: list\u003Cgoal.call\u003E?\n  - OnToolCall: goal.call?\n  - OnValidateResponse: goal.call?\n  - OnStream: goal.call?\n  - Schema: object?\n  - Format: text?\n  - Model: text?\n  - ContinuePreviousConversation: bool = false\n  - Temperature: number = 0\n  - TopP: number?\n  - MaxTokens: number = 16000\n  - MaxToolCalls: number = 10\n  - MaxValidationRetries: number = 0\n  - Cache: bool = true\n\u2192 returns data\n\nNotes:\n\u0060llm.query system=\u2026, user=\u2026\u0060 \u2192 single \u0060Messages\u0060 parameter of type \u0060list\u003Cllmmessage\u003E\u0060:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060json\n[{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022system\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022\u2026\u0022},{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022user\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022\u2026\u0022}]\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n\u0060schema=\u2026\u0060 \u2192 \u0060Schema\u0060 parameter. If JSON-shaped, set \u0060\u0022type\u0022: \u0022json\u0022\u0060 and emit as a structured object (not a string containing JSON).\n\nExamples:\n  Step text: \u0060system: analyze sentiment, user: %comment%, schema: {sentiment: string}, write to %result%\u0060\nMapping: \u0060llm.query Messages([list\u003CLlmMessage\u003E] [{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022system\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022analyze sentiment\u0022},{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022user\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022%comment%\u0022}]), Schema([string] {sentiment: string}) | variable.set Name([string] %result%), Value([object] %!data%)\u0060\n\n\n\n## variable.set [no-cache]\n\nDescription:\nRead, write, and inspect PLang runtime variables in the current scope\n\nAssign a value to a named variable, optionally coercing to a type or setting only when unset\n\nParameters:\n  - Name: %var%\n  - Value: object\n  - Type: type?\n  - AsDefault: bool = false\n\u2192 returns data\n\nNotes:\n\u0060set %x% = \u2026\u0060 is ONE \u0060variable.set\u0060. Emit the \u0060Type\u0060 parameter only when the step gives an explicit \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E[/\u003Ckind\u003E] [strict]\u0060 or \u0060(\u003Ckind\u003E)\u0060 annotation (see the Type reference block); otherwise omit and let the runtime infer.\n\n\u0060set %x% = \u2026 as default\u0060 / \u0022default to\u0022 / \u0022only if unset\u0022 \u2192 plain \u0060variable.set\u0060 with \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022AsDefault\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:true,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022bool\u0022}\u0060. NEVER \u0060code.setDefault\u0060 (that picks a signing/crypto provider \u2014 unrelated to assigning a \u0060%variable%\u0060).\n\n\u0060\u003Cproducer\u003E, write to %x%\u0060 \u2192 the producer \u002B a trailing PEER \u0060variable.set(Name=%x%, Value=%!data%)\u0060 (never a modifier). Don\u0027t add a separate \u0060Type\u0060 \u2014 the producer\u0027s \u0060Data\u003CT\u003E\u0060 (its \u0060\u2192 returns\u0060 line) carries it.\n\nExamples:\n  Step text: \u0060set %x% = 5\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %x%), Value([number] 5)\u0060 \u2014 no \u0060Type\u0060; runtime stamps \u0060{name:\u0022number\u0022,kind:\u0022int\u0022}\u0060 from the literal.\n\n  Step text: \u0060set default %enabled% = true\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %enabled%), Value([bool] true), AsDefault([bool] true)\u0060 \u2014 no \u0060Type\u0060; the value is plain.\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %doc% = \u0022readme.md\u0022 as text\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %doc%), Value([text] readme.md), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022})\u0060\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %img% = \u0022real.gif\u0022 as image/gif strict\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %img%), Value([text] real.gif), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022image\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022gif\u0022,\u0022strict\u0022:true})\u0060\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %n% = \u002242\u0022 as int\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %n%), Value([text] 42), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022int\u0022})\u0060 \u2014 \u0060int\u0060 is a kind of \u0060number\u0060, never a top-level name.\n\n\n\n\n\n## Variables in scope (from prior steps)\n\n\n\n## Type reference\n\n**Primitive type names** (use these as the top-level \u0060name\u0060 in a parameter \u0060type\u0060 field): text, number, bool, object, list, dict, datetime, date, time, duration, guid, image, video, audio, path, bytes\n\n**Every parameter wrapper has three fields**: \u0060name\u0060 (the parameter name), \u0060value\u0060 (the actual value), \u0060type\u0060 (the value\u0027s PLang type as a structured \u0060{name, kind?, strict?}\u0060 dict). \u0060type\u0060 is ONE field \u2014 never split into sibling \u0060type\u0060 \u002B \u0060kind\u0060 keys.\n\nExamples of complete wrappers:\n\n- raw value \u00605\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:5,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022int\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u00603.14\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:3.14,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022decimal\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060\u0022hi\u0022\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:\u0022hi\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060\u0022readme.md\u0022\u0060 (a string literal \u2014 its value IS the 9 characters \u0022readme.md\u0022, which is text, NOT a markdown document) \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:\u0022readme.md\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060true\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:true,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022bool\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060{a:1, b:2}\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:{\u0022a\u0022:1,\u0022b\u0022:2},\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022object\u0022}}\u0060\n\nA bare string literal is \u0060text\u0060 with **no kind** \u2014 never promote it by its spelling. A file extension in a literal (\u0060.md\u0060, \u0060.jpg\u0060, \u0060.csv\u0060) does NOT make the value that kind: the value is the path string, not the content it points at. A \u0060kind\u0060 on a literal comes from exactly two places, never the spelling:\n- an explicit \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E\u0060 the developer wrote, or\n- a producing action that read the real content/path (e.g. \u0060read file.md\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{text, md}\u0060 \u2014 there the value IS the markdown).\n\nA reference fundamental (\u0060image\u0060, \u0060video\u0060, \u0060audio\u0060, \u0060path\u0060) is never tagged onto a raw literal \u2014 there is no image literal, only a path. The LLM emits \u0060{name: image}\u0060 only when the developer wrote \u0060as image\u0060; the runtime parses the kind from the path.\n\nA parameter whose DECLARED schema type is \u0060type\u0060 (e.g. \u0060variable.set.Type\u0060) carries a type entity AS ITS VALUE. The wrapper is:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022Type\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022md\u0022},\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022type\u0022}}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n\u0060value\u0060 is the type entity \u0060{name, kind?, strict?}\u0060; \u0060type\u0060 is the wrapper\u0027s own type field, set to \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022type\u0022}\u0060.\n\n**Kind vocabulary** \u2014 for each \u0060name\u0060, the kinds you may emit under it (a kind is the file extension or numeric precision):\n\n| name | kind |\n|---|---|\n| audio | m4a, ogg, mp3, wav, flac, aac |\n| text | xml, csv, yaml, md, txt, ini, json, yml |\n| video | flv, webm, avi, mp4, mov, mkv |\n| image | tiff, png, heic, svg, gif, bmp, tif, jpeg, jpg, webp |\n| number | int, long, decimal, double |\n\n\nRules:\n- \u0060string\u0060 is NOT a name \u2014 use \u0060text\u0060. \u0060int\u0060/\u0060long\u0060/\u0060decimal\u0060/\u0060double\u0060 are NOT names \u2014 use \u0060number\u0060 with the precision as the kind.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cname\u003E\u0022}\u0060. For a reference fundamental (\u0060image\u0060/\u0060video\u0060/\u0060audio\u0060/\u0060path\u0060) the runtime parses the kind from the value\u0027s path; for \u0060text\u0060 no kind is derived from a literal\u0027s spelling.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cname\u003E\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022\u003Ckind\u003E\u0022}\u0060.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E strict\u0060 \u2192 adds \u0060\u0022strict\u0022:true\u0060. Strict on a name with no kind is allowed (no-op).\n- Step-text \u0060(\u003Ckind\u003E)\u0060 after a write target \u2192 match the kind to its name in the table above. \u0060(json)\u0060/\u0060(csv)\u0060/\u0060(xml)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060text\u0060; \u0060(int)\u0060/\u0060(long)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060number\u0060; \u0060(gif)\u0060/\u0060(jpg)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060image\u0060. Unknown free strings pass through as \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cthat\u003E\u0022}\u0060.\n\n\n**Catalog types referenced by this step\u0027s actions** (record/enum field shapes; primitives stay in the Primitive list above, kinds in the table above):\n\n- \u0060goal\u0060: { name: text, description: text, comment: text, visibility: visibility, inputParameters: dict\u003Ctext,text\u003E }\n- \u0060llmmessage\u0060: { role: text, content: text, images: list\u003Ctext\u003E }\n- \u0060visibility\u0060: Private | Public\n\n\n## Compile this exact line\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\nllm.query Messages=[{"Role":"system","Content":"# Step Compiler\n\nYou are the PLang compiler. The planner gave you the **set of actions** a step uses (unordered). You order them, nest modifiers, fill parameter values from the step text, and emit one \u0060formal\u0060 line plus the matching \u0060actions[]\u0060.\n\nEach picked action\u0027s parameter schema, **Notes**, **Examples**, and the **Type reference** are in the user message below \u2014 authoritative for that action\u0027s shape. Read them first. This prompt is the cross-cutting kernel.\n\n## Core rule: map the clauses \u2014 nothing more, nothing less\n\nWalk the step text clause by clause. Each clause that does work maps to exactly the action(s) it names.\n\n- **Emit only what a clause names.** If the text gives no value for an optional parameter, omit it. If no clause calls for a second action, don\u0027t add one \u2014 never invent a peer or modifier (no stray \u0060variable.get\u0060, \u0060file.read\u0060, \u0060cache.wrap\u0060) the text didn\u0027t ask for.\n- **Never return an empty \u0060actions\u0060 list for a step that has a clause.** Every real step maps to at least one action: \u0060set %x% = %y%\u0060 \u2192 one \u0060variable.set\u0060; \u0060call X\u0060 \u2192 one \u0060goal.call\u0060. If the planner\u0027s set genuinely lacks a needed action, emit the \u0060missing-actions\u0060 error \u2014 never return nothing.\n\nMost steps are one action per clause. \u0022This looks too simple\u0022 is almost always right.\n\n## Write \u0060formal\u0060 first\n\nA one-line render of the chain; \u0060actions[]\u0060 then mirrors it exactly.\n\n\u0060module.action(ParamName=value, ...)\u0060 \u2014 real schema param names. Quote strings; keep \u0060%vars%\u0060 verbatim; numbers/bools unquoted; lists \u0060[...]\u0060; objects \u0060{k:v}\u0060.\n- Modifier follows its host with \u0060 | \u0060 : \u0060host(...) | error.handle(Actions=[recovery(...)])\u0060\n- Peer follows with \u0060 , \u0060 : \u0060condition.if(...) , goal.call(...)\u0060\n- Nested action values use \u0060[...]\u0060 with the same syntax.\n\n\u0060formal\u0060 and \u0060actions[]\u0060 MUST match exactly \u2014 every \u0060Param=value\u0060 in one appears in the other, no extras either way.\n\n## Modifiers vs peers\n\nOnly THREE actions are modifiers \u2014 \u0060error.handle\u0060, \u0060cache.wrap\u0060, \u0060timeout.after\u0060 \u2014 and they go in the host action\u0027s \u0060modifiers[]\u0060. Use one only when the step has a clause like \u0060on error \u2026\u0060, \u0060cache for \u2026\u0060, \u0060timeout after \u2026\u0060. A \u0060cache=\u0060 *parameter* on \u0060llm.query\u0060 is NOT cache.wrap.\n\nEverything else (\u0060goal.call\u0060, \u0060variable.set\u0060, \u0060condition.if\u0060, \u0060loop.foreach\u0060, \u0060output.write\u0060, \u0060file.*\u0060, \u0060error.throw\u0060, \u2026) is a **peer** in the top-level \u0060actions[]\u0060, never in \u0060modifiers[]\u0060. \u0060if X, call Y\u0060 and \u0060foreach X, call Y\u0060 are two peers.\n\n## \u0060write to %x%\u0060 and \u0060%!data%\u0060\n\n\u0060\u2026, write to %x%\u0060 \u2192 a trailing peer \u0060variable.set(Name=%x%, Value=%!data%)\u0060 after the producer (never a modifier). \u0060%!data%\u0060 is the immediately preceding action\u0027s return value \u2014 use it ONLY to thread one action\u0027s result into the next when the text says so. It is not a fill-in for an unsupplied slot.\n\n## Output shape\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060json\n{\u0022formal\u0022:\u0022...\u0022,\u0022actions\u0022:[...],\u0022confidence\u0022:\u0022VeryHigh|High|Medium|Low|VeryLow\u0022,\u0022explanation\u0022:\u0022...\u0022,\u0022errors\u0022:[],\u0022warnings\u0022:[]}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nEach action: \u0060{module, action, parameters:[{name, value, type}], modifiers?:[...]}\u0060. \u0060module\u0060 is a single identifier: \u0060ui.render\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022module\u0022:\u0022ui\u0022,\u0022action\u0022:\u0022render\u0022}\u0060, never \u0060{\u0022module\u0022:\u0022ui.render\u0022,...}\u0060. Omit \u0060explanation\u0060 at High/VeryHigh; otherwise one sentence on the uncertainty. Drop confidence to Low/VeryLow when the verb doesn\u0027t really match any action you were given.\n\n## Parameters \u0026 types\n\n- \u0060name\u0060 is always the literal schema property name (\u0060Name\u0060, \u0060Value\u0060, \u0060GoalName\u0060, \u2026). A \u0060%var%\u0060 marker in a schema means \u0022takes a variable reference\u0022 \u2014 it is never a parameter name and says nothing about the runtime type. Don\u0027t raise warnings over type or letter-case differences.\n- Type names come from the per-step Type reference (primitive names \u002B kind table \u002B catalog types) \u2014 don\u0027t invent. \u0060text\u0060 not \u0060string\u0060; \u0060number\u0060 carries \u0060int/long/decimal/double\u0060 as its *kind*; lists are \u0060list\u003CT\u003E\u0060. A JSON object/array value uses \u0060type:\u0022json\u0022\u0060 as a structured value.\n- Omit nullable params (\u0060?\u0060) when the text gives no value. NEVER emit \u0060\u0022\u0022\u0060 or copy a type descriptor (\u0060actor?\u0060, \u0060eventtype\u0060) into a value slot.\n\n## Intermediates \u0026 compound conditions\n\n- To branch on a producer\u0027s property, capture into a temp \u0060__conditionReturn__\u0060 and reference \u0060%__conditionReturn__.X%\u0060.\n- \u0060if A and B, call C\u0060 \u2192 two \u0060condition.if\u0060 peers \u002B the \u0060goal.call\u0060; add \u0060warnings:[{\u0022key\u0022:\u0022expanded-condition\u0022,\u0022message\u0022:\u0022...\u0022}]\u0060.\n\n## Errors\n\n- \u0060missing-actions\u0060 (top-level, exact key) \u2014 the set lacks an action the step needs; emit and stop, don\u0027t fabricate a partial chain.\n- Also: \u0060actionNotFound\u0060, \u0060insufficientContext\u0060 (top-level); \u0060ambiguousMapping\u0060, \u0060possibleTypo\u0060 (per action).\n\nNever invent action names (\u0060list.append\u0060/\u0060push\u0060/\u0060insert\u0060 don\u0027t exist \u2014 use \u0060list.add\u0060). Preserve \u0060%name%\u0060 literally everywhere, including \u0060return\u0060.\n"},{"Role":"user","Content":"## Step text (the line to compile)\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\nllm.query Messages=%messages%, Schema={description: string, steps: list\u003C{index: int, actions: list\u003Cstring\u003E, confidence: string, explanation?: string}\u003E}, cache=%!build.cache%, write to %plan%\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n## What to map to \u2014 the planner picked these actions\n\nllm.query, variable.set\n\n## Action detail (parameters \u002B notes)\n\n\n\n\n## llm.query\n\nDescription:\nSend prompts to an LLM and receive structured or streamed responses, with optional tool use\n\nSend a conversation (system \u002B user messages) to an LLM and return the response, with optional schema or tool use\n\nParameters:\n  - Messages: list\u003Cllmmessage\u003E\n  - Tools: list\u003Cgoal.call\u003E?\n  - OnToolCall: goal.call?\n  - OnValidateResponse: goal.call?\n  - OnStream: goal.call?\n  - Schema: object?\n  - Format: text?\n  - Model: text?\n  - ContinuePreviousConversation: bool = false\n  - Temperature: number = 0\n  - TopP: number?\n  - MaxTokens: number = 16000\n  - MaxToolCalls: number = 10\n  - MaxValidationRetries: number = 0\n  - Cache: bool = true\n\u2192 returns data\n\nNotes:\n\u0060llm.query system=\u2026, user=\u2026\u0060 \u2192 single \u0060Messages\u0060 parameter of type \u0060list\u003Cllmmessage\u003E\u0060:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060json\n[{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022system\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022\u2026\u0022},{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022user\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022\u2026\u0022}]\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n\u0060schema=\u2026\u0060 \u2192 \u0060Schema\u0060 parameter. If JSON-shaped, set \u0060\u0022type\u0022: \u0022json\u0022\u0060 and emit as a structured object (not a string containing JSON).\n\nExamples:\n  Step text: \u0060system: analyze sentiment, user: %comment%, schema: {sentiment: string}, write to %result%\u0060\nMapping: \u0060llm.query Messages([list\u003CLlmMessage\u003E] [{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022system\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022analyze sentiment\u0022},{\u0022Role\u0022:\u0022user\u0022,\u0022Content\u0022:\u0022%comment%\u0022}]), Schema([string] {sentiment: string}) | variable.set Name([string] %result%), Value([object] %!data%)\u0060\n\n\n\n## variable.set [no-cache]\n\nDescription:\nRead, write, and inspect PLang runtime variables in the current scope\n\nAssign a value to a named variable, optionally coercing to a type or setting only when unset\n\nParameters:\n  - Name: %var%\n  - Value: object\n  - Type: type?\n  - AsDefault: bool = false\n\u2192 returns data\n\nNotes:\n\u0060set %x% = \u2026\u0060 is ONE \u0060variable.set\u0060. Emit the \u0060Type\u0060 parameter only when the step gives an explicit \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E[/\u003Ckind\u003E] [strict]\u0060 or \u0060(\u003Ckind\u003E)\u0060 annotation (see the Type reference block); otherwise omit and let the runtime infer.\n\n\u0060set %x% = \u2026 as default\u0060 / \u0022default to\u0022 / \u0022only if unset\u0022 \u2192 plain \u0060variable.set\u0060 with \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022AsDefault\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:true,\u0022type\u0022:\u0022bool\u0022}\u0060. NEVER \u0060code.setDefault\u0060 (that picks a signing/crypto provider \u2014 unrelated to assigning a \u0060%variable%\u0060).\n\n\u0060\u003Cproducer\u003E, write to %x%\u0060 \u2192 the producer \u002B a trailing PEER \u0060variable.set(Name=%x%, Value=%!data%)\u0060 (never a modifier). Don\u0027t add a separate \u0060Type\u0060 \u2014 the producer\u0027s \u0060Data\u003CT\u003E\u0060 (its \u0060\u2192 returns\u0060 line) carries it.\n\nExamples:\n  Step text: \u0060set %x% = 5\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %x%), Value([number] 5)\u0060 \u2014 no \u0060Type\u0060; runtime stamps \u0060{name:\u0022number\u0022,kind:\u0022int\u0022}\u0060 from the literal.\n\n  Step text: \u0060set default %enabled% = true\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %enabled%), Value([bool] true), AsDefault([bool] true)\u0060 \u2014 no \u0060Type\u0060; the value is plain.\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %doc% = \u0022readme.md\u0022 as text\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %doc%), Value([text] readme.md), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022})\u0060\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %img% = \u0022real.gif\u0022 as image/gif strict\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %img%), Value([text] real.gif), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022image\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022gif\u0022,\u0022strict\u0022:true})\u0060\n\n  Step text: \u0060set %n% = \u002242\u0022 as int\u0060\nMapping: \u0060variable.set Name([variable] %n%), Value([text] 42), Type([type] {\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022int\u0022})\u0060 \u2014 \u0060int\u0060 is a kind of \u0060number\u0060, never a top-level name.\n\n\n\n\n\n## Variables in scope (from prior steps)\n\n\n\n## Type reference\n\n**Primitive type names** (use these as the top-level \u0060name\u0060 in a parameter \u0060type\u0060 field): text, number, bool, object, list, dict, datetime, date, time, duration, guid, image, video, audio, path, bytes\n\n**Every parameter wrapper has three fields**: \u0060name\u0060 (the parameter name), \u0060value\u0060 (the actual value), \u0060type\u0060 (the value\u0027s PLang type as a structured \u0060{name, kind?, strict?}\u0060 dict). \u0060type\u0060 is ONE field \u2014 never split into sibling \u0060type\u0060 \u002B \u0060kind\u0060 keys.\n\nExamples of complete wrappers:\n\n- raw value \u00605\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:5,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022int\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u00603.14\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:3.14,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022number\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022decimal\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060\u0022hi\u0022\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:\u0022hi\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060\u0022readme.md\u0022\u0060 (a string literal \u2014 its value IS the 9 characters \u0022readme.md\u0022, which is text, NOT a markdown document) \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:\u0022readme.md\u0022,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060true\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:true,\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022bool\u0022}}\u0060\n- raw value \u0060{a:1, b:2}\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022X\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:{\u0022a\u0022:1,\u0022b\u0022:2},\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022object\u0022}}\u0060\n\nA bare string literal is \u0060text\u0060 with **no kind** \u2014 never promote it by its spelling. A file extension in a literal (\u0060.md\u0060, \u0060.jpg\u0060, \u0060.csv\u0060) does NOT make the value that kind: the value is the path string, not the content it points at. A \u0060kind\u0060 on a literal comes from exactly two places, never the spelling:\n- an explicit \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E\u0060 the developer wrote, or\n- a producing action that read the real content/path (e.g. \u0060read file.md\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{text, md}\u0060 \u2014 there the value IS the markdown).\n\nA reference fundamental (\u0060image\u0060, \u0060video\u0060, \u0060audio\u0060, \u0060path\u0060) is never tagged onto a raw literal \u2014 there is no image literal, only a path. The LLM emits \u0060{name: image}\u0060 only when the developer wrote \u0060as image\u0060; the runtime parses the kind from the path.\n\nA parameter whose DECLARED schema type is \u0060type\u0060 (e.g. \u0060variable.set.Type\u0060) carries a type entity AS ITS VALUE. The wrapper is:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022Type\u0022,\u0022value\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022text\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022md\u0022},\u0022type\u0022:{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022type\u0022}}\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\n\u0060value\u0060 is the type entity \u0060{name, kind?, strict?}\u0060; \u0060type\u0060 is the wrapper\u0027s own type field, set to \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022type\u0022}\u0060.\n\n**Kind vocabulary** \u2014 for each \u0060name\u0060, the kinds you may emit under it (a kind is the file extension or numeric precision):\n\n| name | kind |\n|---|---|\n| audio | m4a, ogg, mp3, wav, flac, aac |\n| text | xml, csv, yaml, md, txt, ini, json, yml |\n| video | flv, webm, avi, mp4, mov, mkv |\n| image | tiff, png, heic, svg, gif, bmp, tif, jpeg, jpg, webp |\n| number | int, long, decimal, double |\n\n\nRules:\n- \u0060string\u0060 is NOT a name \u2014 use \u0060text\u0060. \u0060int\u0060/\u0060long\u0060/\u0060decimal\u0060/\u0060double\u0060 are NOT names \u2014 use \u0060number\u0060 with the precision as the kind.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cname\u003E\u0022}\u0060. For a reference fundamental (\u0060image\u0060/\u0060video\u0060/\u0060audio\u0060/\u0060path\u0060) the runtime parses the kind from the value\u0027s path; for \u0060text\u0060 no kind is derived from a literal\u0027s spelling.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E\u0060 \u2192 \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cname\u003E\u0022,\u0022kind\u0022:\u0022\u003Ckind\u003E\u0022}\u0060.\n- Step-text \u0060as \u003Cname\u003E/\u003Ckind\u003E strict\u0060 \u2192 adds \u0060\u0022strict\u0022:true\u0060. Strict on a name with no kind is allowed (no-op).\n- Step-text \u0060(\u003Ckind\u003E)\u0060 after a write target \u2192 match the kind to its name in the table above. \u0060(json)\u0060/\u0060(csv)\u0060/\u0060(xml)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060text\u0060; \u0060(int)\u0060/\u0060(long)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060number\u0060; \u0060(gif)\u0060/\u0060(jpg)\u0060 \u2192 \u0060image\u0060. Unknown free strings pass through as \u0060{\u0022name\u0022:\u0022\u003Cthat\u003E\u0022}\u0060.\n\n\n**Catalog types referenced by this step\u0027s actions** (record/enum field shapes; primitives stay in the Primitive list above, kinds in the table above):\n\n- \u0060goal\u0060: { name: text, description: text, comment: text, visibility: visibility, inputParameters: dict\u003Ctext,text\u003E }\n- \u0060llmmessage\u0060: { role: text, content: text, images: list\u003Ctext\u003E }\n- \u0060visibility\u0060: Private | Public\n\n\n## Compile this exact line\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\nllm.query Messages=%messages%, Schema={description: string, steps: list\u003C{index: int, actions: list\u003Cstring\u003E, confidence: string, explanation?: string}\u003E}, cache=%!build.cache%, write to %plan%\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nProduce the actions for this step \u2014 map the line above verbatim. Copy every identifier, path, and argument exactly as written (e.g. a goal name \u0060Folder/Goal\u0060 keeps \u0060/Goal\u0060; a \u0060%var%\u0060 stays a \u0060%var%\u0060).\n"}], Schema={description: string, steps: list\u003C{index: int, actions: list\u003Cstring\u003E, confidence: string, explanation?: string}\u003E}, cache=%!build.cache%, write to System.Collections.Generic.Dictionary`2[System.String,System.Object]\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nProduce the actions for this step \u2014 map the line above verbatim. Copy every identifier, path, and argument exactly as written (e.g. a goal name \u0060Folder/Goal\u0060 keeps \u0060/Goal\u0060; a \u0060%var%\u0060 stays a \u0060%var%\u0060).\n"}], Schema={description: string, steps: list<{index: int, actions: list<string>, confidence: string, explanation?: string}>}, cache=%!build.cache%, write to System.Collections.Generic.Dictionary`2[System.String,System.Object]


